1565
00:58:40,991 --> 00:58:43,451
"I played cards under the tree."

1566
00:58:43,451 --> 00:58:44,821
Do you play cards?

1567
00:58:45,791 --> 00:58:47,691
(She gets caught.)

1568
00:58:47,751 --> 00:58:50,221
"We had corn and soda,"

1569
00:58:50,221 --> 00:58:53,591
"which the neighbor brought. They were delicious."

1570
00:58:53,591 --> 00:58:54,791
(She put a lot of effort.)

1571
00:58:54,891 --> 00:58:56,921
You'd be a great student.

1572
00:58:57,651 --> 00:59:01,551
That's why she regrets not being able to study.

1573
00:59:01,551 --> 00:59:02,591
I can understand.

1574
00:59:02,721 --> 00:59:04,921
(She finishes writing.)

1575
00:59:05,791 --> 00:59:08,621
When you feel amazing,

1576
00:59:09,321 --> 00:59:10,751
you can do this.

1577
00:59:11,051 --> 00:59:12,091
Do this.

1578
00:59:12,091 --> 00:59:14,391
Try this, ma'am.

1579
00:59:14,391 --> 00:59:16,451
Try it. It's what many young people do.

1580
00:59:16,451 --> 00:59:17,491
That's right.

1581
00:59:17,621 --> 00:59:19,191
When you meet your neighbors...

1582
00:59:19,951 --> 00:59:21,551
and they say, "I saw you on TV."

1583
00:59:22,251 --> 00:59:24,491
(Respond with this gesture.)

1584
00:59:24,491 --> 00:59:25,491
Did you see me?

1585
00:59:25,651 --> 00:59:27,191
If they say, "I saw you on TV"...

1586
00:59:27,191 --> 00:59:28,451
Is it funny?

1587
00:59:28,451 --> 00:59:31,021
This is the sign for our team.

1588
00:59:31,021 --> 00:59:32,191
Okay.

1589
00:59:32,191 --> 00:59:34,691
Do you remember your mom?

1590
00:59:35,051 --> 00:59:37,151
Of course I remember my parents.

1591
00:59:37,151 --> 00:59:38,491
- Is that so? - Also,

1592
00:59:38,651 --> 00:59:40,721
- I remember my brother. - Your brother?

1593
00:59:41,521 --> 00:59:43,921
Whom would I call my brother when he's not here?

1594
00:59:44,751 --> 00:59:46,521
I can't call him.

1595
00:59:46,951 --> 00:59:50,551
Let's say you buy a car after getting your license.

1596
00:59:50,591 --> 00:59:53,851
I know your mother isn't alive anymore.

1597
00:59:53,851 --> 00:59:55,321
Your brother isn't alive, is he?

1598
00:59:55,751 --> 00:59:59,591
Where would you like to go with...

1599
00:59:59,991 --> 01:00:01,251
your mother and brother?

1600
01:00:01,451 --> 01:00:03,391
I'd like to go after I learn.

1601
01:00:03,391 --> 01:00:04,851
Where would you like to go?

1602
01:00:04,851 --> 01:00:07,721
I'd take them to sightseeing...

1603
01:00:07,721 --> 01:00:09,591
in the world.

1604
01:00:09,591 --> 01:00:10,591
In the world?

1605
01:00:10,591 --> 01:00:12,121
The world is nice.

1606
01:00:12,121 --> 01:00:15,051
Is there anything they haven't seen,

1607
01:00:15,051 --> 01:00:17,421
- Right. but you've seen it?

1608
01:00:17,421 --> 01:00:18,751
Is there anything you want to show them?

1609
01:00:18,751 --> 01:00:20,191
The world got better.

1610
01:00:20,191 --> 01:00:22,691
These days,

1611
01:00:22,791 --> 01:00:26,991
people take a trip with their parents on the weekend.

1612
01:00:27,451 --> 01:00:29,721
They go to Ssanggyesa or to eat.

1613
01:00:29,721 --> 01:00:32,251
My generation couldn't do that for our parents.

1614
01:00:32,891 --> 01:00:34,121
I regret it.

1615
01:00:34,621 --> 01:00:36,921
Would you like to go anywhere?

1616
01:00:36,921 --> 01:00:38,591
I couldn't buy them anything.

1617
01:00:38,591 --> 01:00:40,051
I couldn't give them an allowance.

1618
01:00:40,751 --> 01:00:43,621
I regret not being able to do that.

1619
01:00:43,621 --> 01:00:45,751
Have you seen cherry blossoms...

1620
01:00:45,751 --> 01:00:47,091
with your parents...

1621
01:00:47,091 --> 01:00:48,251
when you were a child?

1622
01:00:48,251 --> 01:00:50,051
No, I haven't.

1623
01:00:50,051 --> 01:00:51,521
That's why I regret it.

1624
01:00:53,691 --> 01:00:55,691
These days,

1625
01:00:55,951 --> 01:01:00,051
people take their parents to somewhere nice.

1626
01:01:00,051 --> 01:01:02,251
At that time, we couldn't go.

1627
01:01:02,251 --> 01:01:04,551
We couldn't because we were poor.

1628
01:01:05,621 --> 01:01:08,191
How about writing something based on imagination?

1629
01:01:08,691 --> 01:01:12,421
How about you write a letter to your mother?

1630
01:01:12,951 --> 01:01:13,951
Write a poem for your mother.

1631
01:01:13,951 --> 01:01:15,051
A poem?

1632
01:01:16,051 --> 01:01:18,721
You haven't written anything to your mother.

1633
01:01:18,721 --> 01:01:21,491
Now that you learned how to write,

1634
01:01:21,951 --> 01:01:23,321
you can write something to her.

1635
01:01:23,851 --> 01:01:27,051
Now that I learned how to write,

1636
01:01:27,691 --> 01:01:29,021
I can write...

1637
01:01:30,191 --> 01:01:31,651
a letter to my mother.

1638
01:01:33,121 --> 01:01:34,191
Then...

1639
01:01:35,851 --> 01:01:38,091
I lived this long.

1640
01:01:39,121 --> 01:01:40,491
I finally write to my mother.

1641
01:01:46,091 --> 01:01:48,721
I lived a good life.

1642
01:01:49,621 --> 01:01:51,191
I'd give you money,

1643
01:01:53,421 --> 01:01:54,851
buy you delicious food,

1644
01:01:54,851 --> 01:01:56,491
and nice clothes.

1645
01:01:56,891 --> 01:01:58,521
I couldn't do them before,

1646
01:01:59,451 --> 01:02:00,851
but finally I can.

1647
01:02:01,751 --> 01:02:03,421
Shall I write that?

1648
01:02:10,021 --> 01:02:12,051
It's my dream. I'll write about my dream.

1649
01:02:12,051 --> 01:02:13,091
That sounds good.

1650
01:02:13,491 --> 01:02:16,751
How do I write "red"?

1651
01:02:16,751 --> 01:02:19,121
- Red. - Red.

1652
01:02:19,121 --> 01:02:21,051
- Red? - Yes.

1653
01:02:21,521 --> 01:02:22,721
(She writes carefully.)

1654
01:02:22,721 --> 01:02:24,751
That's correct.

1655
01:02:24,751 --> 01:02:26,251
- Is this correct? - Yes.

1656
01:02:26,721 --> 01:02:28,451
What's the next character?

1657
01:02:28,751 --> 01:02:30,691
- Red? - Right.

1658
01:02:30,791 --> 01:02:32,421
- D. - D.

1659
01:02:32,851 --> 01:02:34,591
- Is it D? - Yes.

1660
01:02:34,591 --> 01:02:36,121
- It's D. - Is this right?

1661
01:02:36,251 --> 01:02:38,821
- Is this right? - D.

1662
01:02:38,821 --> 01:02:40,551
- Did you say D? - Yes.

1663
01:02:44,491 --> 01:02:46,451
Is this correct?

1664
01:02:46,591 --> 01:02:48,321
Red.

1665
01:02:48,321 --> 01:02:50,321
- That looks interesting. - Red Jeep.

1666
01:02:50,321 --> 01:02:51,551
Jeep?

1667
01:02:51,551 --> 01:02:53,321
- J. - It's J.

1668
01:02:53,321 --> 01:02:55,121
- It's Jeep. - Right.

1669
01:02:55,121 --> 01:02:56,751
(Her heart flutters.)

1670
01:02:56,751 --> 01:02:58,051
- Is this right? - Yes.

1671
01:02:58,051 --> 01:02:59,751
That's correct.

1672
01:02:59,751 --> 01:03:01,321
- It's P. - P.

1673
01:03:01,321 --> 01:03:03,321
- P. - That's right.

1674
01:03:03,821 --> 01:03:05,751
It's P.

1675
01:03:05,751 --> 01:03:07,691
It's "Red Jeep".

1676
01:03:09,651 --> 01:03:15,021
(They write each letter with sincerity.)

1677
01:03:17,191 --> 01:03:18,651
(What kind of poems did they write?)

1678
01:03:21,191 --> 01:03:22,191
Have a seat here.

1679
01:03:23,451 --> 01:03:24,591
Please sit here.

1680
01:03:24,591 --> 01:03:25,621
(They lead them to comfortable seats.)

1681
01:03:26,621 --> 01:03:28,651
- Here's a blanket. - I don't need it.

1682
01:03:28,691 --> 01:03:29,721
Please take it.

1683
01:03:29,951 --> 01:03:32,391
I'm dressed warmly, so I don't need a blanket.

1684
01:03:33,051 --> 01:03:35,121
It's cold. Let's get under it together.

1685
01:03:35,121 --> 01:03:37,421
- We're good ma'am. - Here.

1686
01:03:37,421 --> 01:03:40,121
- Joon Ho's not cold. - Don't be ridiculous.

1687
01:03:40,251 --> 01:03:41,421
We'll cover ourselves together.

1688
01:03:41,421 --> 01:03:43,051
(They get under the blanket together.)

1689
01:03:43,051 --> 01:03:45,591
This is how close we've gotten.

1690
01:03:46,151 --> 01:03:48,791
- It's cold. - This isn't necessary.

1691
01:03:48,791 --> 01:03:51,521
- Here. - Thank you so much.

1692
01:03:51,521 --> 01:03:52,521
(Thank you.)

1693
01:03:53,151 --> 01:03:57,221
(Poem under the Moonlight)

1694
01:03:57,951 --> 01:04:00,921
Welcome to the first...

1695
01:04:00,921 --> 01:04:05,321
One Night Two Days Poem under the Moonlight.

1696
01:04:05,321 --> 01:04:06,921
(They'll recite their poems under the moonlight.)

1697
01:04:07,321 --> 01:04:09,151
This is nice.

1698
01:04:09,151 --> 01:04:11,221
Am I supposed to read mine in front of everyone?

1699
01:04:11,221 --> 01:04:13,051
First up is Kim Gil Ja.

1700
01:04:13,051 --> 01:04:15,951
Please call her Poet Adele.

1701
01:04:15,951 --> 01:04:17,051
(Poet Adele)

1702
01:04:17,051 --> 01:04:18,791
Is she the Adele of Hadong?

1703
01:04:19,251 --> 01:04:21,221
(Adele's my name.)

1704
01:04:22,221 --> 01:04:24,721
I'd like to write a letter to my late husband.

1705
01:04:24,721 --> 01:04:25,921
(A letter to her late husband)

1706
01:04:25,921 --> 01:04:27,451
That's a great idea.

1707
01:04:28,051 --> 01:04:30,391
(The words she wasn't able to say to him)

1708
01:04:31,421 --> 01:04:33,491
(She wrote one word after the next.)

1709
01:04:35,021 --> 01:04:37,491
(A poem for her husband)

1710
01:04:39,951 --> 01:04:42,851
You can start by saying the title.

1711
01:04:42,851 --> 01:04:46,021
(Joon Young helps her relax.)

1712
01:04:46,021 --> 01:04:48,021
This is "Confession".

1713
01:04:48,751 --> 01:04:50,651
"Dear my husband."

1714
01:04:51,521 --> 01:04:54,451
"It's been 10 years since..."

1715
01:04:54,721 --> 01:04:56,691
"you left me."

1716
01:04:56,991 --> 01:05:00,891
"It's been 10 years since I moved to Hadong."

1717
01:05:02,051 --> 01:05:05,691
"Thanks to the fresh air here,"

1718
01:05:06,051 --> 01:05:08,821
"I've been able to stay away from hospitals."

1719
01:05:09,321 --> 01:05:12,791
"Life hasn't been bad I guess."

1720
01:05:12,791 --> 01:05:15,991
(Life hasn't been bad I guess.)

1721
01:05:15,991 --> 01:05:19,291
"Jeong Yeon, how are you doing over there?"

1722
01:05:20,591 --> 01:05:23,151
"I'm curious..."

1723
01:05:23,891 --> 01:05:25,321
"if you're in good health."

1724
01:05:26,891 --> 01:05:29,521
(How are you doing?)

1725
01:05:30,421 --> 01:05:33,951
(Today, I finally get to tell you how much I miss you.)

1726
01:05:35,891 --> 01:05:37,421
"I'm curious."

1727
01:05:38,491 --> 01:05:40,821
"Mi Jung, Hyang Sook,"

1728
01:05:41,391 --> 01:05:43,791
"Jin Seok, Bong Seok,"

1729
01:05:43,851 --> 01:05:48,321
"and Jeong Yeon are all doing great."

1730
01:05:48,521 --> 01:05:50,751
"Byung Min and Da Min too,"

1731
01:05:50,951 --> 01:05:53,321
"so don't worry about them."

1732
01:05:53,751 --> 01:05:57,391
"I hope you'll hang in there until I join you someday."

1733
01:05:58,121 --> 01:06:01,251
"What I wasn't able to tell you in person,"

1734
01:06:01,421 --> 01:06:03,521
"I finally get to tell you..."

1735
01:06:03,521 --> 01:06:05,021
"today."

1736
01:06:06,851 --> 01:06:09,421
(The words she wasn't able to say to him.)

1737
01:06:11,091 --> 01:06:14,291
"I love you."

1738
01:06:15,991 --> 01:06:18,751
(She delivered the heartfelt letter very calmly.)

1739
01:06:19,291 --> 01:06:22,021
- That was amazing. - It really was.

1740
01:06:22,021 --> 01:06:23,691
What an amazing poem.

1741
01:06:23,791 --> 01:06:25,421
You wrote a letter.

1742
01:06:25,421 --> 01:06:29,021
- It's for my late husband. - Your late husband.

1743
01:06:29,121 --> 01:06:31,751
(When you profess your love)

1744
01:06:31,751 --> 01:06:33,151
(And hug the one you love)

1745
01:06:33,151 --> 01:06:35,921
She said it calmly, but it came from the heart.

1746
01:06:35,921 --> 01:06:38,791
- It was sweet. - It was a love poem.

1747
01:06:38,791 --> 01:06:39,991
I loved it.

1748
01:06:40,221 --> 01:06:42,951
She bravely read it although she was first.

1749
01:06:42,951 --> 01:06:46,891
- I agree. - It's not something that's easy to do.

1750
01:06:46,891 --> 01:06:49,791
- These represent her and her husband. - The flowers.

1751
01:06:49,821 --> 01:06:51,551
She draw roses.

1752
01:06:52,921 --> 01:06:57,221
Anyway, you just heard from Poet Adele.

1753
01:06:57,221 --> 01:06:58,321
Thank you.

1754
01:07:00,221 --> 01:07:01,951
She has a pen name too.

1755
01:07:01,951 --> 01:07:02,951
It's Velvet.

1756
01:07:02,951 --> 01:07:04,491
(Poet Velvet)

1757
01:07:04,491 --> 01:07:06,751
- She's Velvet. - Velvet.

1758
01:07:06,751 --> 01:07:09,221
- Velvet? - Like Red Velvet?

1759
01:07:09,221 --> 01:07:11,221
She should have one too. How about Blackpink?

1760
01:07:11,221 --> 01:07:14,221
- She loves pink. - Blackpink it is then.

1761
01:07:14,221 --> 01:07:15,421
Blackpink?

1762
01:07:15,421 --> 01:07:17,891
- Next up is... - Blackpink.

1763
01:07:17,891 --> 01:07:19,421
(Next up is Lee Soon Ja.)

1764
01:07:19,421 --> 01:07:21,391
Poet Blackpink.

1765
01:07:21,391 --> 01:07:23,921
Soon Ja has wrote many poems so far.

1766
01:07:23,921 --> 01:07:25,821
She writes one every day.

1767
01:07:26,691 --> 01:07:29,021
(Her fully packed schedule)

1768
01:07:29,591 --> 01:07:32,221
(After she learned how to read and write,)

1769
01:07:32,951 --> 01:07:35,691
(she spent every day enjoying the education.)

1770
01:07:36,491 --> 01:07:39,691
(A passionate student and poet full of joy)

1771
01:07:40,621 --> 01:07:43,891
(She'll write a poem about the happiness of learning.)

1772
01:07:45,221 --> 01:07:47,821
(A heartfelt poem)

1773
01:07:48,751 --> 01:07:51,321
(What did she come up with?)

1774
01:07:52,721 --> 01:07:54,291
- Should I start? - Sure.

1775
01:07:55,051 --> 01:07:58,721
"A Day as Happy as Today".

1776
01:07:59,521 --> 01:08:02,321
"As a girl, I didn't receive education."

1777
01:08:02,491 --> 01:08:04,391
"I had no friends."

1778
01:08:04,521 --> 01:08:06,651
"I was very lonely."

1779
01:08:06,991 --> 01:08:10,121
"My parents believe that women shouldn't..."

1780
01:08:10,121 --> 01:08:11,491
"leave the house at night."

1781
01:08:11,491 --> 01:08:13,991
"So every night after dinner,"

1782
01:08:13,991 --> 01:08:17,051
"my father would stand guard outside..."

1783
01:08:17,051 --> 01:08:18,851
"our front gate."

1784
01:08:19,251 --> 01:08:23,121
"Out of loneliness, I cried many nights."

1785
01:08:24,691 --> 01:08:27,491
"Then finally I was offered an opportunity..."

1786
01:08:27,621 --> 01:08:29,821
"to learn how to read and write."

1787
01:08:29,961 --> 01:08:33,091
"Studying at Jeongdong School..."

1788
01:08:33,621 --> 01:08:36,591
"brings me such happiness."

1789
01:08:36,821 --> 01:08:38,691
"A day like today."

1790
01:08:39,251 --> 01:08:42,921
"I wish many future days are just as happy as well."

1791
01:08:43,121 --> 01:08:47,221
"Being so happy, I can't help but laugh."

1792
01:08:48,751 --> 01:08:50,921
- My goodness. - It sounded like a confession.

1793
01:08:50,921 --> 01:08:52,491
Her days of crying is over.

1794
01:08:52,491 --> 01:08:54,391
Her crying is now in the past.

1795
01:08:54,421 --> 01:08:56,891
I was able to feel just how happy studying makes her.

1796
01:08:56,891 --> 01:08:58,121
(A warm poem that conveys her happiness)

1797
01:08:58,121 --> 01:08:59,961
- Thank you so much. - Thank you.

1798
01:08:59,961 --> 01:09:01,621
- I knew it'd be good. - Dong Gu.

1799
01:09:01,621 --> 01:09:03,921
- I loved the title too. - She delivered.

1800
01:09:03,921 --> 01:09:06,621
- It was amazing. - I loved how...

1801
01:09:06,621 --> 01:09:08,921
she was able to make it rhyme.

1802
01:09:08,961 --> 01:09:11,891
This looks like a sign of a seolleongtang restaurant.

1803
01:09:11,891 --> 01:09:13,251
(A seolleongtang restaurant)

1804
01:09:13,251 --> 01:09:14,791
Don't you agree?

1805
01:09:14,791 --> 01:09:18,021
I know. It could be on the menu of one.

1806
01:09:18,021 --> 01:09:22,251
Last but not least, Kang Jeom Soon is up.

1807
01:09:22,251 --> 01:09:25,991
Velvet, it's time to read your poem.

1808
01:09:25,991 --> 01:09:27,891
- Here. - Let's go.

1809
01:09:29,251 --> 01:09:31,821
- What could you write about? - My mother.

1810
01:09:32,121 --> 01:09:35,421
I'd like to write a letter...

1811
01:09:36,691 --> 01:09:38,321
to my mother.

1812
01:09:39,491 --> 01:09:40,591
That...

1813
01:09:41,421 --> 01:09:42,421
- It's red. - Right.

1814
01:09:42,421 --> 01:09:44,691
(Thanks to Tae Hyun and Defconn...)

1815
01:09:45,021 --> 01:09:46,391
- Red. - Like this?

1816
01:09:46,391 --> 01:09:48,751
(She writes from the heart.)

1817
01:09:49,551 --> 01:09:50,821
It's a red car.

1818
01:09:50,821 --> 01:09:51,991
Yes, a red one.

1819
01:09:51,991 --> 01:09:53,791
(She's always wanted to drive a red car.)

1820
01:09:54,221 --> 01:09:56,421
- Does this look like a person? - It does.

1821
01:09:57,521 --> 01:10:00,921
(She draws a younger self of hers.)

1822
01:10:00,921 --> 01:10:02,621
- In the past? - That's right.

1823
01:10:02,621 --> 01:10:06,121
(A poem that's more like a dream)

1824
01:10:06,851 --> 01:10:10,321
Kang Jeom Soon.

1825
01:10:10,321 --> 01:10:11,751
(It's now time to listen to her dream.)

1826
